04563nam a22006735i 9780292795228DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212009txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927952287 a10.7560/7194462doi  a(DE-B1597)588470  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aE99.K26bR53 1996eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a976.4/12201 aNutini, Hugo G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSocial Stratification in Central Mexico, 1500-2000 /cHugo G. Nutini, Barry L. Isaac. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART ONE Historical Overview -- tOne: ESTATES AND CLASSES -- tTwo: RACE AND ETHNICITY -- tThree: HACIENDAS AND THEIR WORKERS -- tPART TWO The Postrevolutionary Period (1920–2000) -- tFour: THE UPPER CLASSES Aristocracy, Plutocracy, Political Class, and Prestige Upper-Middle Class -- tFive: THE MIDDLE CLASSES -- tSix: THE URBAN LOWER CLASSES -- tSeven: THE INDIAN-MESTIZO TRANSITION From Ethnic Estates to Social Classes -- tEight: EXPRESSION AND SOCIAL CLASS -- tCONCLUSION -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Aztec and colonial Central Mexico, every individual was destined for lifelong placement in a legally defined social stratum or estate. Social mobility became possible after independence from Spain in 1821 and increased after the 1910–1920 Revolution. By 2000, the landed aristocracy that was for long Mexico's ruling class had been replaced by a plutocracy whose wealth derives from manufacturing, commerce, and finance—but rapid growth of the urban lower classes reveals the failure of the Mexican Revolution and subsequent agrarian reform to produce a middle-class majority. These evolutionary changes in Mexico's class system form the subject of Social Stratification in Central Mexico, 1500–2000, the first long-term, comprehensive overview of social stratification from the eve of the Spanish Conquest to the end of the twentieth century. The book is divided into two parts. Part One concerns the period from the Spanish Conquest of 1521 to the Revolution of 1910. The authors depict the main features of the estate system that existed both before and after the Spanish Conquest, the nature of stratification on the haciendas that dominated the countryside for roughly four centuries, and the importance of race and ethnicity in both the estate system and the class structures that accompanied and followed it. Part Two portrays the class structure of the post-revolutionary period (1920 onward), emphasizing the demise of the landed aristocracy, the formation of new upper and middle classes, the explosive growth of the urban lower classes, and the final phase of the Indian-mestizo transition in the countryside.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEthnohistoryzTexaszGulf Coast. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zTexaszGulf Coast. 0aKarankawa IndiansxAntiquities. 0aKarankawa IndiansxGovernment relations. 0aKarankawa IndiansxHistoryxSources. 0aSocial stratificationzMexicoxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aIsaac, Barry L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795228/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK